<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Multidistrict Lit Man § 4:21<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Multidistrict Litigation Manual</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20190501"><bop/><bos/>May 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>David F. Herr[<footnote.reference refid="If2d91c516b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">a0</footnote.reference>]</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I97b7f560933b11da99e2b07024dacc26"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Part</label.name><label.designator>I.</label.designator><headtext>Handling Cases Before the Judicial Panel on Multidistrict Litigation</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><prop.head toc-guid="Ib978dbb0933b11da99e2b07024dacc26"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>4.</label.designator><headtext>Procedure Before the Panel</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copyright (c) 2017 Thomson/RIA All rights reserved.</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="I94ee9362e1e311da9c26e67ca3b71335"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>4:21.</label.designator><headtext>Hearing—Right to hearing</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The Panel Rules provide for a hearing of contested transfer or remand matters.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If2d96a706b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">1</footnote.reference>] The Panel deals with many matters in which the parties may not desire to be heard and the Panel&apos;s procedures, therefore, are stringent in requiring parties to request hearing or be deemed to waive it. <eos/><bos/>It is not uncommon for parties, even in significant, multiparty cases, to waive argument.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If2d991816b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">2</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>A party must respond to the motion, show cause order, or conditional order in order to be heard. <eos/><bos/>Failure to respond will be deemed acquiescence in the motion or order.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If2d991826b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">3</footnote.reference>] The Panel Rules specifically provide that oral argument will not be allowed a party who has not made a written submission absent Panel approval for good cause shown.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If2d9b8906b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">4</footnote.reference>] Despite the Panel&apos;s rule limiting argument to parties who have submitted briefs, it appears that the rule may be flexibly applied.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If2d9dfa06b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">5</footnote.reference>] Nonetheless, it is prudent to submit a timely motion or responsive brief in order to secure the right to argue orally before the Panel.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></section.body></section><author.footnotes><footnote ID="If2d91c516b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>a0</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Maslon Edelman Borman &amp; Brand, LLP, Minneapolis, Minnesota.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></author.footnotes><footnote.block><footnote ID="If2d96a706b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>J.P.M.L. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0304913988" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USMULTIDISTLITR11.1" w-pub-number="1000604" ID="I56ffa6506b3e11e9a5a983883834314b">R. 11.1(c)</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>The Panel rules are reproduced in <cite.query w-ref-type="NA" w-normalized-cite="MDLITMANs4:34" w-pub-number="185218" ID="If2d991806b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">§ 4:34</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If2d991816b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See, e.g., <cite.query w-src-number="0304913988" w-serial-number="1999277776" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000999" ID="I57001b816b3e11e9a5a983883834314b">In re Vitamins Antitrust Class Actions, 1999 WL 1211449 (D.D.C. 1999)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If2d991826b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>J.M.D.L. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0304913988" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USMULTIDISTLITR6.1" w-pub-number="1000604" ID="I570c02606b3e11e9a5a983883834314b">R. 6.1(c) (motions)</cite.query>, <cite.query w-src-number="0304913988" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USMULTIDISTLITR7.1" w-pub-number="1000604" ID="I570c02616b3e11e9a5a983883834314b">7.1(d)</cite.query> (conditional transfer orders), 8.1(c) (show cause orders), 10.2 (conditional remand orders).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If2d9b8906b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>J.P.M.L. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0304913988" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USMULTIDISTLITR11.1" w-pub-number="1000604" ID="I570ec1806b3e11e9a5a983883834314b">R. 11.1(d)(i)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If2d9dfa06b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><ital>See</ital> <cite.query w-src-number="0304913988" w-serial-number="1971105726" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000345" w-pinpoint-page="510" ID="I570f0fa16b3e11e9a5a983883834314b">In re IBM Antitrust Litigation, 328 F. Supp. 509, 510 (J.P.M.L. 1971)</cite.query> (party heard at argument despite not filing brief).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>MDLITMAN § 4:21<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
